Looking at all the feedback, it is clear that we have a classic &#39;Developer vs. User&#39; situation on
our hands. On the technical side, the project is a total win. The database is secure, the math
for delivery fees and loyalty points is perfect, and the code is organized so well that any
other developer could jump in and understand it immediately.
However, once real people started using the site, we discovered that &#39;working perfectly&#39;
isn&#39;t the same thing as &#39;feeling easy to use.&#39; The biggest takeaway was definitely the
navigation bar. Stanley, Josh, and Evie-Mae all felt it was way too big, almost like a wall
blocking them from seeing the products. The lesson here is that people visit the site to shop,
not to stare at a giant header. By shrinking that bar and making it &#39;sticky,&#39; we can keep the
navigation handy without it getting in the way of the actual farm produce.
We also learned a lot about how people want to browse. Danil pointed out that using
dropdown menus to pick items is a bit like trying to read a restaurant menu through a
keyhole—you can only see one thing at a time. To fix this, moving to a grid layout would be
a game-changer. It would turn the shop into a digital farmer&#39;s market where everything is
on display at once, making it much more visual and inviting.
Maison Bond brought up a great point about the loyalty points. Even though the logic
behind the points is solid, the explanation of why they matter isn&#39;t quite persuasive enough
yet. It is a good reminder that even the best features need a bit of &#39;marketing&#39; to make users
actually want to use them. Combined with the feedback about the &#39;bright green&#39; being a bit
hard on the eyes, we have a clear path forward.
Moving into Phase 2, we aren&#39;t looking to fix &#39;broken&#39; code—because the code isn&#39;t broken.
Instead, we are going to focus on the polish. By darkening the green for better readability,
slimming down the header, and adding those smooth animations users asked for, we can
take a technically perfect system and make it a pleasure to use for the local community.
